# 25d8bb90b2c446878107538d435165b1
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:2
msgid "WCCP Service Configuration"
msgstr ""

# 6f717619436a408385ab6629d3106173
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:23
msgid ""
"The service definition file is used by :ref:`traffic_wccp` and :ref"
":`traffic-server` directly. The elements in the security definition file "
"are inspired by the `WCCP RFC (8/2012) <http://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-"
"mclaggan-wccp-v2rev1-00>`_.  There is also an older version of the RFC "
"that shows up commonly in search results, `WCCP (4/2001) "
"<https://tools.ietf.org/id/draft-wilson-wrec-wccp-v2-01.txt>`_, and was "
"the RFC reference used in the original WCCP support for Traffic Server "
"several years ago."
msgstr ""

# e98a8df14d5d44d8b92742caef07609f
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:27
msgid ""
"A sample service group file is included in the source tree under "
"cmd/traffic_wccp."
msgstr ""

# e39c62d0ca6e4554839814bcd5a64c4e
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:30
msgid "Security Section"
msgstr ""

# e75520f8e2234013abfbdd7c56561e6b
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:32
msgid ""
"In the security section, you can define a password shared between the "
"WCCP Client and the WCCP router.  This password is used to encrypt the "
"WCCP traffic.  It is optional, but highly recommended."
msgstr ""

# e36295e4cc89436cbc2edb987b33a0e8
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:34
msgid "Attributes in this section"
msgstr ""

# 6da7ea71c2e748f1a4de41f19496e761
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:36
msgid "option  - Must be set to MD5 if you want to encrypt your WCCP traffic"
msgstr ""

# 5ac5cb05a05c4604bb313728ddb7fa1a
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:38
msgid "key – The same password that you set with the associated WCCP router."
msgstr ""

# 671d167b9cbb4f279f620f2b3adc2e28
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:41
msgid "Services Section"
msgstr ""

# bdff9313860e43ecbf587e87cb282087
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:43
msgid ""
"In the services section you can define a list of service groups.  Each "
"top level entry is a separate service group."
msgstr ""

# 53f93cc639f340eba7ec024f4e1b9293
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:45
msgid "Service group attributes include"
msgstr ""

# ae4888d8aa5547acb6c66a8c06dcbd4d
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:47
msgid ""
"name – A name for the service.  Not used in the rest of the WCCP "
"processing."
msgstr ""

# 797f53d76ba041de81a5e808b03678c0
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:49
msgid ""
"description – A description of the service.  Again, not used in the rest "
"of the WCCP processing."
msgstr ""

# 28fc395dc06d4102b90b08cf2ac1c79b
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:51
msgid ""
"id - The security group ID.  It must match the service group ID that has "
"been defined on the associated WCCP router.  This is the true service "
"group identifier from the WCCP perspective."
msgstr ""

# efa9d5eec8254aeb9362b6cd637efaec
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:53
msgid ""
"type – This defines the type of service group either “STANDARD” or "
"“DYNAMIC”.  There is one standard defined service group, HTTP with the id"
" of 0.  The 4/2001 RFC indicates that id’s 0-50 are reserved for well "
"known service groups.  But more recent 8/2012 RFC indicates that values 0"
" through 254 are valid service id’s for dynamic services.  To avoid "
"differences with older WCCP routers, you probably want to  avoid dynamic "
"service ID’s 0 through 50."
msgstr ""

# 1bd5037dc859495fafb1cd7924fa147d
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:55
msgid ""
"priority – This is a value from 0 to 255.  The higher number is a higher "
"priority.  Well known (STANDARD) services are set to a value of 240.  If "
"there are multiple service groups that could match a given packet, the "
"higher priority service group is applied. RFC  For example, you have "
"service group 100 defined for packets with destination port 80, and "
"service group 101 defined for packets with source port 1024.  For a "
"packet with destination port set to 80 and source port set to 1024, the "
"priorities of the service groups would need to be compared to determine "
"which service group applies."
msgstr ""

# 876cc585f78047a3b006bea57d80d8bb
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:57
msgid ""
"protocol – This is IP protocol number that should match.  Generally this "
"is set to 6 (TCP) or 17 (UDP)."
msgstr ""

# d1e0bf75cb2c4c40b46d6f33fdd5e5d5
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:59
msgid ""
"assignment – WCCP supports multiple WCCP clients supporting a single "
"service group.  However, the current WCCP client implementation in "
"Traffic Server assumes there is only a single WCCP client, and so creates"
" assignment tables that will direct all traffic to that WCCP client.  The"
" assignment type is either hash or mask, and if it is not set, it "
"defaults to hash.  If Traffic Server ever supports more than one cache, "
"it will likely only support a balanced hash assignment.  The mask/value "
"assignment seems to be better suited to situations where the traffic "
"needs to be more strongly controlled."
msgstr ""

# f6c520bdef4a491db0388f8be71e3445
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:61
msgid ""
"primary-hash – This is the element of the packet that is used to compute "
"the primary key.  The value options are src_ip, dst_ip, src_port, or  "
"dst_port. This entry is a list, so multiple values can be specified.  In "
"that case, all the specified packet attributes will be used to compute "
"the hash bucket.  In the current implementation, the primary hash value "
"does not matter, since the client always generates a hash table that "
"directs all matching traffic to it.  But if multiple clients are ever "
"supported, knowledge of the local traffic distribution could be used to "
"pick a packet attribute that will better spread traffic over the WCCP "
"clients."
msgstr ""

# a89115ca73ca47b5aa7b9eadbe7aa9b6
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:62
msgid ""
"alt-hash – The protocol supports a two level hash.  This attribute is a "
"list with the same value options as for primary-hash.  Again, since the "
"current Traffic Server implementation only creates assignment tables to a"
" single client, specifying the alt-hash values does nothing."
msgstr ""

# 37dd01212b424e97b90a066a333d6327
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:64
msgid ""
"ports – This is a list of port values.  Up to 8 port values may be "
"included in a service group definition."
msgstr ""

# cc0305df2de24600bc441cad2477d53b
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:66
msgid ""
"port-type – This attribute can have the value of src or dst.  If not "
"specified, it defaults to dst.  It indicates whether the port values "
"should be interpreted as source ports or destination ports."
msgstr ""

# 979826773a684407af3007b0514e0ecc
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:68
msgid ""
"forward – This is a list.  The list of the values can be GRE or L2.  This"
" advertises how the client wants to process WCCP packets.  GRE means that"
" the packets will be delivered in a GRE tunnel.  This is the default.  L2"
" means that the client is on the same network and can get traffic "
"delivered to it from the router by L2 routing (MAC addresses)."
msgstr ""

# 76928fa46fbf4fbfb1fe53f5ee8356b9
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:70
msgid ""
"return – The WCCP protocol allows a WCCP client to decline a packet and "
"return it back to the router.  The current WCCP client implementation "
"never does this.  The value options are the same as for the forward "
"attribute."
msgstr ""

# 1438bb01602a46f6a834a1f293da084a
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:72
msgid ""
"routers – This is the list of router addresses the WCCP client "
"communicates with.  The WCCP protocols allows for multiple WCCP routers "
"to be involved in a service group.  The multiple router scenario has at "
"most been lightly tested in the Traffic Server implementation."
msgstr ""

# 690c9922241c4c888c49050ac72839f1
#: ../../admin-guide/transparent-proxy/wccp-service-config.en.rst:74
msgid ""
"proc-name – This attribute is only used by traffic_wccp.  It is not used "
"in the traffic_server WCCP support.  This is the path to a process’ PID "
"file.  The service group is advertised to the WCCP router if the process "
"identified in the PID file is currently operational."
msgstr ""

